{"title_page": "Disarmament of the Lou Nuer", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Disarmament of the Lou Nuer\n| place       = Northern [[Jonglei State]]\n| date        = December 2005 \u2013 18 May 2006 <br />({{Age in years and months|month1=12|year1=2005|day1=1|month2=5|day2=18|year2=2006}})\n| result      = [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] victory\n| combatants_header = \n| combatant1  = {{Flagicon|South_Sudan|size=22px}} [[Southern Sudan Autonomous Region (2005\u201311)|Southern Sudan]]\n*{{Flagicon|South_Sudan|size=22px}} [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]]\n| combatant2  = {{Flagicon image|Nuer White Army Flag.svg|size=22px}} Lou Nuer [[Nuer White Army|White Army]]<br/>{{Flagicon image|Flag of the South Sudan Defence Force.svg|size=22px}} [[South Sudan Defence Forces (militia)|SSDF]] forces of Thomas Maboir<br/>{{Flagicon image|Flag of the South Sudan Defence Force.svg|size=22px}} [[South Sudan Defence Forces (militia)|SSDF]] forces of [[Simon Gatwitch]]<br/> '''''Supported by:''''' <br/> {{Flagicon|Sudan|size=22px}}[[Sudan]]\n| commander1  = {{Flagicon|South_Sudan|size=22px}} [[Peter Bol Koang|Peter Bol Kong]]\n| commander2  = {{Flagicon image|Flag of the South Sudan Defence Force.svg|size=22px}} Simon Wojong\n| strength1   = 3,000-9,000\n| strength2   = 6,000-20,000\n| casualties1 = 400-700\n| casualties2 = 1,200\n| casualties3 = 213 civilians killed\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Sudan internal conflicts}}\n}}\n\nThe [[disarmament]] of the [[Lou Nuer]] was a forcible disarmament campaign undertaken by the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] in [[Southern Sudan Autonomous Region (2005\u201311)|Southern Sudan]] in December 2005. While other groups had been peacefully [[Disarmament|disarmed]], the Lou section of the [[Nuer people|Nuer]] in Northern [[Jonglei State]] refused to comply. The SPLA organized a force under [[Peter Bol Koang|Peter Bol Kong]] to forcibly disarm the Lou Nuer, whose [[Nuer White Army|White Army]] resisted until a defeat in the battle of [[Motot]], after which they fled the area.\n\n== Background ==\nWhile the [[Comprehensive Peace Agreement]] that ended the [[Second Sudanese Civil War]] in January 2005 called for the [[disarmament]] of other armed groups, it had little guidance on disarming civilians.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/DC866C7CA6654FCB8525726100724E53-Full_Report.pdf|title=Anatomy of civilian disarmament in Jonglei State: Recent experiences and implications|last=|first=|date=November 2006|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> However, the [[SPLM]], the major political party in [[Southern Sudan Autonomous Region (2005\u201311)|Southern Sudan]], decided to disarm civilians in order to reduce ethnic violence, reserve the right to bear arms for the party, eliminate armed groups backed by [[Sudan]], and ensure the security of its territory before challenging Sudan on border issues.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://issafrica.org/research/papers/sudan-peoples-liberation-army-disarmament-in-jonglei-and-its-implications|title=Sudan People's Liberation Army: Disarmament in Jonglei and its implications|last=ISSAfrica.org|date=2007-04-06|website=ISS Africa|language=en|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> Disarmament started in Western [[Jonglei State]] and moved east, with the lightly armed [[Dinka people|Dinka]] and later the Jikan Nuer disarming relatively peacefully.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sudantribune.com/spip.php?article16921|title=Fragile disarmament in South Sudan - Sudan Tribune: Plural news and views on Sudan|website=www.sudantribune.com|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.smallarmssurveysudan.org/fileadmin/docs/working-papers/HSBA-WP-05-White-Army.pdf|title=The White Army: An Introduction and Overview|last=Young|first=John|date=June 2007|website=|page=21|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In late 2005, the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] assigned Gen. [[Peter Bol Koang|Peter Bol Kong]], a Lou Nuer with an ethnically mixed force, to disarm the Lou Nuer.\n\nIn December, the [[Pastoralism|pastoral]] Lou and Gawaar [[Nuer people|Nuer]] asked the Dinka in [[Duk County]] permission to graze on their lands.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.smallarmssurvey.org/fileadmin/docs/A-Yearbook/2007/en/full/Small-Arms-Survey-2007-Chapter-10-EN.pdf|title=Persistent Instability: ARMED VIOLENCE AND INSECURITY IN SOUTH SUDAN|last=|first=|date=2007|website=|page=334|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> However, unlike previous years, the Dinka insisted that the Lou and Gawaar disarm before coming in their territories. A series of meetings began in [[Khorfulus County]] where the [[Jonglei State]] government said that the groups needed to either join the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] or turn their weapons in, or else they would be forcibly disarmed. The Jonglei governor also promised compensation for the weapons, but it was unclear were the funding would come from or who it would go to. The meetings were long, and the mediators consumed approximately 1,300 of the Lou Nuer's cattle.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Lou Nuer refused to disarm, saying they needed their weapons for protection from the [[Murle people|Murle]], who had not been disarmed. Skirmishes began between the Lou Nuer and the SPLA.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== The Disarmament Campaign ==\n[[File:Jonglei Administrative Map-sr.svg|thumb|A map of Jonglei state. Most of the fighting occurred in [[Uror County]] (\u0423\u0420\u041e\u0420). [[Motot]] (\u041c\u0432\u043e\u0442 \u0422\u043e\u0442) is also shown.|alt=]]\nAt the end of January 2006, the [[Nuer White Army|White Army]] forces launched a major attack on the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] which left about 60 dead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/war/south-sudan-2006.htm|title=South Sudan - Tribal Warfare 2006|website=www.globalsecurity.org|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> In the mayhem, hundreds of SPLA forces were scattered into the dry lands and died of hunger and thirst.<ref name=\":1\" /> Wutnyang Gatkek, a Gawaar [[Nuer people|Nuer]] spiritual leader and a former influential white army member was killed when he went to [[Yuai]] on behalf of the SPLA to promote disarmament.<ref name=\":3\" /> His death and the deaths of SPLA soldiers led to demands for a swift and hard military response. The Security Committee of the [[Southern Sudan autonomous region (2005\u20132011)|Government of Southern Sudan]] met and was split, with the leader of the [[SPLM]], [[Salva Kiir]], wanting restraint and with [[Riek Machar]], a Nuer, wanting a rapid response. Machar's side won, and Gen. [[Peter Bol Koang|Peter Bol Kong]] was given a free hand to disarm the Lou Nuer.<ref name=\":1\" /> Major battles began with Bol Kong's disarmament forces fighting the White Army, the forces of Thomas Maboir (though Maboir did not fight), and a section of the [[South Sudan Defence Forces (militia)|SSDF]] forces of [[Simon Gatwitch]] under his deputy Simon Wojong.<ref name=\":3\" /> A conference was held from February 27 to March 7 in Yuai with the White Army and leading figures of the Government of Southern Sudan in another attempt to get the Lou Nuer to peacefully disarm.<ref name=\":1\" /> Riek Machar, regarded as the founder of the White Army, announced its dissolution, but the youth were determined to keep their arms.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nFrom April to May there were frequent sightings of a helicopter arriving at Simon Wojong's camp near [[Yuai]], and it was concluded that this was a [[Sudanese Armed Forces]] helicopter bringing supplies.<ref name=\":1\" /> By May 2006, the Lou [[Nuer people|Nuer]] economy was in tatters and many [[Nuer White Army|White Army]] fighters had lost most of their cattle.<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Peter Bol Koang|Peter Bol Kong]] arrived in the [[Motot]] area on May 16. After some skirmishes with the White Army and Simon Wojong's forces, the battle of [[Motot]] occurred on May 18, in which 113 White Army fighters were killed to just one [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] soldier killed.<ref name=\":1\" /> The White Army and the forces of Thomas Maboir fled north, heavy looting cattle and property from the local population. The SPLA also looted the fleeing forces.<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Simon Gatwitch]] claimed to have ordered his forces north as well to avoid conflict with the SPLA, and they reached Dolip Hill. The military campaign was over.\n\n== Aftermath ==\nOn May 20 [[Peter Bol Koang|Peter Bol Kong]] called together local authorities, and disarmament began and lasted for two months. The disarmament collected more than 3,000 weapons and was claimed to be 95 percent effective.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the next place in line for disarmament, [[Akobo, South Sudan|Akobo]], Akobo Commissioner Doyak Choal, shocked by the violence to the east, quickly organized a  disarmament lead by traditional leaders without the involvement of the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]]. The Akobo disarmament was successful and turned out 1,400 weapons.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAbout 400 [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] soldiers and 1,200 [[Nuer White Army|White Army]] fighters died in the disarmament of the Lou Nuer.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The SPLA burned the huts of White Army members, so about 1,000 huts were burned.<ref name=\":4\" /> The violence made it so the locals could not plant and the SPLA was not supplied with food so it had to live off the locals' animals, creating serious food shortages after the conflict.<ref name=\":1\" /> The White Army was defeated, but it would later be reformed and again challenge the SPLA.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:History of South Sudan]]\n[[Category:Nuer people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Disarmament of the Lou Nuer\n| place       = Northern [[Jonglei State]]\n| date        = December 2005 \u2013 18 May 2006 <br />({{Age in years and months|month1=12|year1=2005|day1=1|month2=5|day2=18|year2=2006}})\n| result      = [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] victory\n| combatants_header = \n| combatant1  = {{Flagicon|South_Sudan|size=22px}} [[Southern Sudan Autonomous Region (2005\u201311)|Southern Sudan]]\n*{{Flagicon|South_Sudan|size=22px}} [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]]\n| combatant2  = {{Flagicon image|Nuer White Army Flag.svg|size=22px}} Lou Nuer [[Nuer White Army|White Army]]<br/>{{Flagicon image|Flag of the South Sudan Defence Force.svg|size=22px}} [[South Sudan Defence Forces (militia)|SSDF]] forces of Thomas Maboir<br/>{{Flagicon image|Flag of the South Sudan Defence Force.svg|size=22px}} [[South Sudan Defence Forces (militia)|SSDF]] forces of [[Simon Gatwitch]]<br/> '''''Supported by:''''' <br/> {{Flagicon|Sudan|size=22px}}[[Sudan]]\n| commander1  = {{Flagicon|South_Sudan|size=22px}} [[Peter Bol Koang|Peter Bol Kong]]\n| commander2  = {{Flagicon image|Flag of the South Sudan Defence Force.svg|size=22px}} Simon Wojong\n| strength1   = 3,000-9,000\n| strength2   = 6,000-20,000\n| casualties1 = 400-700\n| casualties2 = 1,200\n| casualties3 = 213 civillians killed\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Sudan internal conflicts}}\n}}\n\nThe [[disarmament]] of the [[Lou Nuer]] was a forcible disarmament campaign undertaken by the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] in [[Southern Sudan Autonomous Region (2005\u201311)|Southern Sudan]] in December 2005. While other groups had been peacefully [[Disarmament|disarmed]], the Lou section of the [[Nuer people|Nuer]] in Northern [[Jonglei State]] refused to comply. The SPLA organized a force under [[Peter Bol Koang|Peter Bol Kong]] to forcibly disarm the Lou Nuer, whose [[Nuer White Army|White Army]] resisted until a defeat in the battle of [[Motot]], after which they fled the area.\n\n== Background ==\nWhile the [[Comprehensive Peace Agreement]] that ended the [[Second Sudanese Civil War]] in January 2005 called for the [[disarmament]] of other armed groups, it had little guidance on disarming civilians.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/DC866C7CA6654FCB8525726100724E53-Full_Report.pdf|title=Anatomy of civilian disarmament in Jonglei State: Recent experiences and implications|last=|first=|date=November 2006|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> However, the [[SPLM]], the major political party in [[Southern Sudan Autonomous Region (2005\u201311)|Southern Sudan]], decided to disarm civilians in order to reduce ethnic violence, reserve the right to bear arms for the party, eliminate armed groups backed by [[Sudan]], and ensure the security of its territory before challenging Sudan on border issues.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://issafrica.org/research/papers/sudan-peoples-liberation-army-disarmament-in-jonglei-and-its-implications|title=Sudan People's Liberation Army: Disarmament in Jonglei and its implications|last=ISSAfrica.org|date=2007-04-06|website=ISS Africa|language=en|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> Disarmament started in Western [[Jonglei State]] and moved east, with the lightly armed [[Dinka people|Dinka]] and later the Jikan Nuer disarming relatively peacefully.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sudantribune.com/spip.php?article16921|title=Fragile disarmament in South Sudan - Sudan Tribune: Plural news and views on Sudan|website=www.sudantribune.com|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.smallarmssurveysudan.org/fileadmin/docs/working-papers/HSBA-WP-05-White-Army.pdf|title=The White Army: An Introduction and Overview|last=Young|first=John|date=June 2007|website=|page=21|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In late 2005, the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] assigned Gen. [[Peter Bol Koang|Peter Bol Kong]], a Lou Nuer with an ethnically mixed force, to disarm the Lou Nuer.\n\nIn December, the [[Pastoralism|pastoral]] Lou and Gawaar [[Nuer people|Nuer]] asked the Dinka in [[Duk County]] permission to graze on their lands.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.smallarmssurvey.org/fileadmin/docs/A-Yearbook/2007/en/full/Small-Arms-Survey-2007-Chapter-10-EN.pdf|title=Persistent Instability: ARMED VIOLENCE AND INSECURITY IN SOUTH SUDAN|last=|first=|date=2007|website=|page=334|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> However, unlike previous years, the Dinka insisted that the Lou and Gawaar disarm before coming in their territories. A series of meetings began in [[Khorfulus County]] where the [[Jonglei State]] government said that the groups needed to either join the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] or turn their weapons in, or else they would be forcibly disarmed. The Jonglei governor also promised compensation for the weapons, but it was unclear were the funding would come from or who it would go to. The meetings were long, and the mediators consumed approximately 1,300 of the Lou Nuer's cattle.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Lou Nuer refused to disarm, saying they needed their weapons for protection from the [[Murle people|Murle]], who had not been disarmed. Skirmishes began between the Lou Nuer and the SPLA.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== The Disarmament Campaign ==\n[[File:Jonglei Administrative Map-sr.svg|thumb|A map of Jonglei state. Most of the fighting occurred in [[Uror County]] (\u0423\u0420\u041e\u0420). [[Motot]] (\u041c\u0432\u043e\u0442 \u0422\u043e\u0442) is also shown.|alt=]]\nAt the end of January 2006, the [[Nuer White Army|White Army]] forces launched a major attack on the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] which left about 60 dead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/war/south-sudan-2006.htm|title=South Sudan - Tribal Warfare 2006|website=www.globalsecurity.