rmishes with the White Army and Simon Wojong's forces, the battle of [[Motot]] occurred on May 18, in which 113 White Army fighters were killed to just one [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] soldier killed.<ref name=\":1\" /> The White Army and the forces of Thomas Maboir fled north, heavy looting cattle and property from the local population. The SPLA also looted the fleeing forces.<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Simon Gatwitch]] claimed to have ordered his forces north as well to avoid conflict with the SPLA, and they reached Dolip Hill. The military campaign was over.\n\n== Aftermath ==\nOn May 20 [[Peter Bol Koang|Peter Bol Kong]] called together local authorities, and disarmament began and lasted for two months. The disarmament collected more than 3,000 weapons and was claimed to be 95 percent effective.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the next place in line for disarmament, [[Akobo, South Sudan|Akobo]], Akobo Commissioner Doyak Choal, shocked by the violence to the east, quickly organized a  disarmament lead by traditional leaders without the involvement of the [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]]. The Akobo disarmament was successful and turned out 1,400 weapons.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAbout 400 [[Sudan People's Liberation Army|SPLA]] soldiers and 1,200 [[Nuer White Army|White Army]] fighters died in the disarmament of the Lou Nuer.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The SPLA burned the huts of White Army members, so about 1,000 huts were burned.<ref name=\":4\" /> The violence made it so the locals could not plant and the SPLA was not supplied with food so it had to live off the locals' animals, creating serious food shortages after the conflict.<ref name=\":1\" /> The White Army was defeated, but it would later be reformed and again challenge the SPLA.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:History of South Sudan]]\n[[Category:Nuer people]]\n", "name_user": "Woodlot", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disarmament_of_the_Lou_Nuer"}
{"title_page": "Clarence Clifton Young", "text_new": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox Congressman \n| name = C. Clifton Young\n| image = Clarence Clifton Young.jpg\n| state=[[Nevada]]\n| district=[[Nevada's At-large congressional district|At-Large]]\n| term_start= January 3, 1953\n| term_end= January 3, 1957\n| preceded= [[Walter S. Baring Jr.]]\n| succeeded= Walter S. Baring Jr.\n| office1= Member of the [[Nevada Senate]]\n| term1= 1966\u20131980\n| office2= Associate Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Nevada|Nevada Supreme Court]] (Seat D)\n| term2= 1985\u20132002\n| preceded2= [[Noel Edwin Manoukian|Noel E. Manoukian]]\n| succeeded2= [[Mark Gibbons]]\n| birth_date= {{birth date|1922|11|7}}\n| birth_place=[[Lovelock, Nevada]]\n| death_date= {{death date and age|2016|4|3|1922|11|7}}\n| death_place=[[Reno, Nevada]]\n| residence=\n| spouse=Jane\n| profession=Attorney\n| religion=\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|}}\n\n'''Clarence Clifton \"Cliff\" Young''' (November 7, 1922 \u2013 April 3, 2016), known as '''C. Clifton Young''', was a [[United States Representative|United States congressman]] from [[Nevada]].\n\nA [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Young was elected to the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] from the state's at-large district in 1952 and re-elected in 1954. He won the Republican nomination for the [[United States Senate]] in 1956 but was defeated by incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Alan Bible]] in a close race.\n\nYoung later served in the [[Nevada Senate]], from 1966 to 1980, and on the [[Nevada Supreme Court]] from 1985 to 2002, including a stint as chief justice (1989\u20131990). He also served as president of the [[National Wildlife Federation]] (1981\u20131983). Young died in Reno, Nevada in 2016 at the age of 93.<ref>[http://mynews4.com/news/local/c-clifton-young-former-nevada-supreme-court-justice-dies-at-93 C. Clifton Young, former Nevada Supreme Court justice dies at 93]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|Y000032}}\n* [https://archive.library.unr.edu/public/repositories/2/resources/19 A Guide to the C. Clifton Young (family) Papers], Special Collections, University Libraries, University of Nevada, Reno.\n* [https://archive.library.unr.edu/public/repositories/2/resources/1211 A Guide to the C. Clifton Young (political) Papers], Special Collections, University Libraries, University of Nevada, Reno.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state=Nevada\n|district=AL\n|before=[[Walter S. Baring Jr.]]\n|years=1953\u20131957\n|after=[[Walter S. Baring Jr.]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{NevadaUSRepresentatives}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, Clarence Clifton}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Nevada]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Nevada]]\n[[Category:Nevada Republicans]]\n[[Category:Nevada state senators]]\n[[Category:Nevada Supreme Court justices]]\n[[Category:People from Lovelock, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Reno, Nevada]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n[[Category:University of Nevada, Reno alumni]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of the Nevada Supreme Court]]\n\n\n{{Nevada-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox Congressman \n| name = C. Clifton Young\n| image = Clarence Clifton Young.jpg\n| state=[[Nevada]]\n| district=[[Nevada's At-large congressional district|At-Large]]\n| term_start= January 3, 1953\n| term_end= January 3, 1957\n| preceded= [[Walter S. Baring Jr.]]\n| succeeded= Walter S. Baring Jr.\n| office1= Member of the [[Nevada Senate]]\n| term1= 1966\u20131980\n| office2= Associate Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Nevada|Nevada Supreme Court]] (Seat D)\n| term2= 1985\u20132002\n| preceded2= [[Noel Edwin Manoukian|Noel E. Manoukian]]\n| succeeded2= [[Mark Gibbons]]\n| birth_date= {{birth date|1922|11|7}}\n| birth_place=[[Lovelock, Nevada]]\n| death_date= {{death date and age|2016|4|3|1922|11|7}}\n| death_place=[[Reno, Nevada]]\n| residence=\n| spouse=Jane\n| profession=Attorney\n| religion=\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|}}\n\n'''Clarence Clifton \"Cliff\" Young''' (November 7, 1922 \u2013 April 3, 2016), known as '''C. Clifton Young''', was a [[United States Representative|United States congressman]] from [[Nevada]].\n\nA [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Young was elected to the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] from the state's at-large district in 1952 and re-elected in 1954. He won the Republican nomination for the [[United States Senate]] in 1956 but was defeated by incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Alan Bible]] in a close race.\n\nYoung later served in the [[Nevada Senate]], from 1966 to 1980, and on the [[Nevada Supreme Court]] from 1985 to 2002, including a stint as chief justice (1989\u20131990). He also served as president of the [[National Wildlife Federation]] (1981\u20131983). Young died in Reno, Nevada in 2016 at the age of 93.<ref>[http://mynews4.com/news/local/c-clifton-young-former-nevada-supreme-court-justice-dies-at-93 C. Clifton Young, former Nevada Supreme Court justice dies at 93]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|Y000032}}\n* [http://dewey.library.unr.edu/xtf/view?docId=ead/96-06-ead.xml A Guide to the C. Clifton Young (family) Papers], Special Collections, University Libraries, University of Nevada, Reno.\n* [https://archive.library.unr.edu/public/repositories/2/resources/19 A Guide to the C. Clifton Young (political) Papers], Special Collections, University Libraries, University of Nevada, Reno.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state=Nevada\n|district=AL\n|before=[[Walter S. Baring Jr.]]\n|years=1953\u20131957\n|after=[[Walter S. Baring Jr.]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{NevadaUSRepresentatives}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, Clarence Clifton}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Nevada]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Nevada]]\n[[Category:Nevada Republicans]]\n[[Category:Nevada state senators]]\n[[Category:Nevada Supreme Court justices]]\n[[Category:People from Lovelock, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Reno, Nevada]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n[[Category:University of Nevada, Reno alumni]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of the Nevada Supreme Court]]\n\n\n{{Nevada-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Steven.Harris", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:correcting external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clarence_Clifton_Young"}
{"title_page": "C. H. Mohammed Koya", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}{{Infobox Indian politician\n| name                = C. H. Mohammad Koya\n| image               = C. H. Mohammed Koya.jpg\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1927|7|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Atholi, Kerala|Atholi]], [[Madras Presidency]], [[British India]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|df=yes|1983|9|28|1927|7|15}}\n| death_place         = [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| office1             = [[List of Chief Ministers of Kerala|8th Chief Minister of Kerala]]\n| term1               = 12 October 1979 - 1 December 1979\n| predecessor1        = [[P. K. Vasudevan Nair]]\n| successor1          = [[President's rule]]\n| party               = [[Indian Union Muslim League]]\n| office2             = [[Speaker (politics)|Speaker]] of [[Kerala Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start2         = 9 June 1961\n| term_end2           = 12 December 1961\n| predecessor2        = [[K. M. Seethi Sahib]]\n| successor2          = [[Alexander Parambithara]]\n| office3             = [[2nd Deputy Chief Minister of Kerala]]\n| term_start3         = 28 December 1981\n| term_end3           = 17 March 1982\n| successor3          = [[Himself]]\n| predecessor3        = [[R. Sankar]]\n| term_start4         = 24 May 1982\n| term_end4           = 28 September 1983\n| successor4          = [[K. Avukader Kutty Naha]]\n| predecessor4        = [[Self]]\n| office5             = Member of Parliament [[Lok Sabha]]\n| term_start5         = 25 February 1962\n| term_end5           = 21 February 1967\n| successor5          = [[Ebrahim Sulaiman Sait]]\n| predecessor5        = [[K. P. Kutti Krishnan Nair]]\n| constituency5       = [[Kozhikode (Lok Sabha constituency)|Kozhikode]]\n| term_start6         = 5 February 1973\n| term_end6           = 20 March 1977\n| successor6          = [[Ebrahim Sulaiman Sait]]\n| predecessor6        = [[Muhammad Ismail]]\n| constituency6       = [[Manjeri (Lok Sabha constituency)|Manjeri]]\n| office7             = [[Member of Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| term_start7         = 5 April 1957\n| term_end7           = 6 March 1962\n| term_start8         = 6 March 1967\n| term_end8           = 5 February 1973\n| term_start9         = 25 March 1977\n| term_end9           = 28 September 1983\n| spouse              = K. K. Amina (married on June 1, 1950)<ref>[http://loksabhaph.nic.in/writereaddata/biodata_1_12/1517.htm Loksabha Profile (1962)]</ref>\n| children            = 2 daughters and a son ([[M. K. Muneer]])\n| website             = \n| footnotes           = \n| date                = 2 November\n| year                = 2007\n| source              = https://web.archive.org/web/20051219145038/http://www.keralacm.gov.in/mohammed.html Govt. of Kerala\n}}\n\n'''C. H. Mohammad Koya''' (15 July 1927 \u2013 28 September 1983), known as '''C. H.<ref name=\":0\">Miller, E. Roland. \"Mappila Muslim Culture\" State University of New York Press, Albany (2015); p. 204, 235-36, 329, 333, and 345.</ref>''', full name '''Cheriyan Kandi Muhammad Koya''', was an Indian politician and journalist<ref name=\":1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20051219145038/http://www.keralacm.gov.in/mohammed.html Chief Minister of Kerala (Official Website)]</ref> who served as the eighth [[Chief Minister of Kerala|Chief Minister]] of [[Kerala]] from October 12 to December 1, 1979. A long time Secretary of the [[Indian Union Muslim League]], he is the only [[Muslims|Muslim]] to be chosen as the Chief Minister of Kerala.<ref name=\":0\" /> As the Minister of Education (Kerala), from 1967 to 1977, C. H. championed the progress of the education of Muslim community in Kerala.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nC. H. was first elected to [[Kerala Legislative Assembly]] in the famous 1957 elections. He went on to hold several key Kerala Cabinet Posts (Deputy Chief Minister, Minister for Education, [[Interior minister|Home Affairs Minister]], and Minister for Finance) under a number of Chief Ministers ([[E. M. S. Namboodiripad]], [[C. Achutha Menon]], [[K. Karunakaran]], [[A. K. Antony]], and [[P. K. Vasudevan Nair]]) in the following decades.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> In 1962 (1962 - 67) and in 1973 (1973-77), he was elected to the [[Parliament of India]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He was a Member in [[University of Kerala|Kerala University]] Senate and served as Chairman, Governing Body, [[National Institute of Technology Calicut|REC, Calicut]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nC. H. was born in 1927 at Atholi, in northern Kerala, to Payampunathil Ali Musliyar and Mariyumma.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>Miller, Roland. E., \"Mappila\" in \"The Encyclopedia of Islam\". Volume VI. E. J. Brill, Leiden. 1987. pp. 458-56.</ref> He co-founded the [[Muslim Students Federation]], or the M. S. F., while a school student  in [[Zamorin's Guruvayurappan College|Calicut Zamorin's College]]. He helped to receive [[Liaquat Ali Khan]] in 1945. C. H. joined the ''[[Chandrika (newspaper)|Chandrika]]'' newspaper, the official organ the Muslim League,<ref>Jeffrey, Robin. \"Politics, Women and Well-Being: How Kerala became a Model\" Palgrave McMillan (1992); 112 and 114.</ref> in 1946. Though only having Intermediate education, C. H. worked his way from Sub-Editor to the Editor of ''Chandrika'' by 1949.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>[http://niyamasabha.org/codes/Speakers%20&%20Deputy%20Speakers%20Book%20Final.pdf Speakers & Deputy Speakers Book \u2013 Kerala Legislative Assembly]</ref>\n\nC. H., who suffered from various health problems like [[diabetes]] and [[hypertension]], died suddenly of a massive [[brain hemorrhage]] at the State Institute of Medical Sciences in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] on 28 September, 1983, while serving as Deputy Chief Minister of Kerala. He was aged just 56 at the time of his death. His body was later taken to his native place, and was buried with full state honours.1<ref name=\":2\" /> He was survived by his mother, wife, three children - two daughters and a son, [[M. K. Muneer]], who later became a noted politician on his own right, and went on to serve as a minister in [[Third A. K. Antony ministry|A. K. Antony]] and [[Oommen Chandy]] ministries.\n\n{{quote box\n| width = 35em\n| bgcolor = #cef4c0\n| align = right\n| quote = \"Young men like C. H. Muhammad Koya realized that violent revolt promised nothing for them [the Kerala Muslims]. Electoral politics, on the other hand, might offer a great deal.\"\n| source = \u2014 '''Robin Jeffrey (historian)<ref>Jeffrey, Robin. \"Politics, Women and Well-Being: How Kerala became a Model\" Palgrave McMillan (1992); 112 and 114.</ref>\n}}\n\n== Career ==\n*[[List of chief ministers of Kerala|Chief Minister of Kerala]] - October 12 to December 1, 1979\n*[[List of Deputy Chief Ministers of Kerala|Deputy Chief Minister of Kerala]] \n** December 28, 1981 - March 17, 1982<ref name=\":1\" /> (2nd [[K. Karunakaran|Karunakaran]] Ministry)\n** May 24, 1982 - September 28, 1983<ref name=\":1\" /> (3rd [[K. Karunakaran|Karunakaran]] Ministry)\n* Speaker, 2nd [[Kerala Legislative Assembly]] \n**09-06-1961 to 10-11-1961<ref name=\":2\">[http://www.niyamasabha.org/codes/members/m424.htm Kerala Legislative Assembly]</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> ([[Pattom A. Thanu Pillai|Pattom]] Ministry)\n* Minister for Education \n**06-03-1967 to 21-10-1969<ref name=\":1\" /> (2nd [[E. M. S. Namboodiripad|E. M. S.]] Ministry)\n* Minister for Education and Home \n**01-11-1969 to 01-08-1970 (1st [[C. Achutha Menon|Achutha Menon]] Ministry)\n**04-10-1970 to 01-03-1973<ref name=\":1\" /> (2nd [[C. Achutha Menon|Achutha Menon]] Ministry)\n* Minister for Education\n**27-04-1977 to 20-12-1977 (1st [[A. K. Antony|Antony]] Ministry)\n**04-10-1978 to 27-10-1978 (1st [[A. K. Antony|Antony]] Ministry)\n**29-10-1978 to 07-10-1979<ref name=\":1\" /> ([[P. K. Vasudevan Nair|P. K. V.]] Ministry)\n* Minister for Finance and Education \n**25-03-1977 to 25-04-1977<ref name=\":1\" /> (1st [[K. Karunakaran|Karunakaran]] Ministry)\n\n* Member of Kerala Legislative Assembly<ref name=\":2\" />\n**1st Assembly (1957\u201359) - Tanur\n**2nd Assembly  (1960\u201364) - Tanur (resigned on 06 March 1962)<ref name=\":2\" />\n**3rd Assembly (1967\u201370) - Mankada\n**4th Assembly (1970\u201377) - Kondotti (resigned on 05 February 1973)<ref name=\":2\" />\n**5th Assembly  (1977\u201379) - Malappuram\n**6th Assembly (1980\u201382) - Manjeri\n**7th Assembly  (1982\u201387) - Manjeri\n\n== Legacy ==\nC. H. was known as a \"fiery and eloquent orator\" and was described by scholar R. E. Miller as \"grassroots star of the Mappila community\" and the \"ranking hero of Muslim youth\" in Kerala.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n* As the Minister of Education (Kerala), C. H. championed the progress of the Mappila community in secular education, but also advocated higher standards in the \"Arabic Colleges\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n* During C. H.'s tenure, the [[University of Calicut]] was established (in northern Kerala) 2nd EMS Govt..<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=TC6zCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA236#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Mappila Muslim Culture: How a Historic Muslim Community in India Has Blended Tradition and Modernity|last=Miller|first=Roland E.|date=2015-04-27|publisher=SUNY Press|year=|isbn=9781438456010|location=|pages=236|language=en}}</ref>\n* C. H. acted a \"bridge-builder\" among various social and religious groups of Kerala.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* C. H. is remembered for his \"spirited\" reply to [[Jawaharlal Nehru]], the [[Prime Minister of India]] (when the latter publicly criticized [[Indian Union Muslim League]] in 1955).<ref name=\":0\" />\n<br>\n{{wide image|Kerala Council of Ministers 1979 CH Mohammed Koya.jpg|700px|Kerala Council of Ministers, 1979, with C. H. Mohammad Koya}}\n\n== Works<ref name=\":2\" /> ==\n\n* ''My Haj pilgrimage''\n* ''Caux-London-Cairo''\n*''The Malaysia I Saw''\n* ''How Legislative Assembly Works''\n*''Soviet Union''\n*''Muslim Rule in India Through Stories''\n* ''Five Days in Sri Lanka''\n* ''Camel to Cadillac''\n*''Travel Around the world''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|C. H. Mohammed Koya}}\n*[https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/interview/story/19791130-rss-is-attacking-the-muslim-minority-mohammed-koya-822379-2014-02-21 C. H. Mohammad Koya: Interview (India Today) 1979]\n*[http://niyamasabha.org/codes/Speakers%20&%20Deputy%20Speakers%20Book%20Final.pdf Speakers & Deputy Speakers Book \u2013 Kerala Legislative Assembly]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before = [[P.K. Vasudevan Nair]] | title = [[Chief Minister of Kerala]] | years = 1979\u2013 1979 | after = [[E.K. Nayanar]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Seethi Sahib]] | title = [[Speaker (politics)|Speaker]] of [[Kerala Legislative Assembly]] | years = 1961\u2013 1961 | after =   Alexander Parambithara}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{United Democratic Front (Kerala)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koya, C. H. Mohammed}}\n[[Category:1927 births|Koya, C.H. Mohammed]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths|Koya, C.H. Mohammed]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Kerala]]\n[[Category:Malayali politicians]]\n[[Category:Kerala politicians]]\n[[Category:Malayali people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Kozhikode]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Kerala Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language writers]]\n[[Category:Indian Union Muslim League politicians]]\n[[Category:3rd Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Deputy chief ministers of Kerala]]\n[[Category:Kerala MLAs 1957\u20131959]]\n[[Category:Kerala MLAs 1960\u20131964]]\n[[Category:Education Ministers of Kerala]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}{{Infobox Indian politician\n| name                = C. H. Mohammad Koya\n| image               = C. H. Mohammed Koya.jpg\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1927|7|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Atholi]], [[Madras Presidency]], [[British India]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|df=yes|1983|9|28|1927|7|15}}\n| death_place         = [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| office1             = [[List of Chief Ministers of Kerala|8th Chief Minister of Kerala]]\n| term1               = 12 October 1979 - 1 December 1979\n| predecessor1        = [[P. K. Vasudevan Nair]]\n| successor1          = [[President's rule]]\n| party               = [[Indian Union Muslim League]]\n| office2             = [[Speaker (politics)|Speaker]] of [[Kerala Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start2         = 9 June 1961\n| term_end2           = 12 December 1961\n| predecessor2        = [[K. M. Seethi Sahib]]\n| successor2          = [[Alexander Parambithara]]\n| office3             = [[2nd Deputy Chief Minister of Kerala]]\n| term_start3         = 28 December 1981\n| term_end3           = 17 March 1982\n| successor3          = [[Himself]]\n| predecessor3        = [[R. Sankar]]\n| term_start4         = 24 May 1982\n| term_end4           = 28 September 1983\n| successor4          = [[K. Avukader Kutty Naha]]\n| predecessor4        = [[Self]]\n| office5             = Member of Parliament [[Lok Sabha]]\n| term_start5         = 25 February 1962\n| term_end5           = 21 February 1967\n| successor5          = [[Ebrahim Sulaiman Sait]]\n| predecessor5        = [[K. P. Kutti Krishnan Nair]]\n| constituency5       = [[Kozhikode (Lok Sabha constituency)|Kozhikode]]\n| term_start6         = 5 February 1973\n| term_end6           = 20 March 1977\n| successor6          = [[Ebrahim Sulaiman Sait]]\n| predecessor6        = [[Muhammad Ismail]]\n| constituency6       = [[Manjeri (Lok Sabha constituency)|Manjeri]]\n| office7             = [[Member of Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| term_start7         = 5 April 1957\n| term_end7           = 6 March 1962\n| term_start8         = 6 March 1967\n| term_end8           = 5 February 1973\n| term_start9         = 25 March 1977\n| term_end9           = 28 September 1983\n| spouse              = K. K. Amina (married on June 1, 1950)<ref>[http://loksabhaph.nic.in/writereaddata/biodata_1_12/1517.htm Loksabha Profile (1962)]</ref>\n| children            = 2 daughters and a son ([[M. K. Muneer]])\n| website             = \n| footnotes           = \n| date                = 2 November\n| year                = 2007\n| source              = https://web.archive.org/web/20051219145038/http://www.keralacm.gov.in/mohammed.html Govt. of Kerala\n}}\n\n'''C. H. Mohammad Koya''' (15 July 1927 \u2013 28 September 1983), known as '''C. H.<ref name=\":0\">Miller, E. Roland. \"Mappila Muslim Culture\" State University of New York Press, Albany (2015); p. 204, 235-36, 329, 333, and 345.</ref>''', full name '''Cheriyan Kandi Muhammad Koya''', was an Indian politician and journalist<ref name=\":1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20051219145038/http://www.keralacm.gov.in/mohammed.html Chief Minister of Kerala (Official Website)]</ref> who served as the eighth [[Chief Minister of Kerala|Chief Minister]] of [[Kerala]] from October 12 to December 1, 1979. A long time Secretary of the [[Indian Union Muslim League]], he is the only [[Muslims|Muslim]] to be chosen as the Chief Minister of Kerala.<ref name=\":0\" /> As the Minister of Education (Kerala), from 1967 to 1977, C. H. championed the progress of the education of Muslim community in Kerala.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nC. H. was first elected to [[Kerala Legislative Assembly]] in the famous 1957 elections. He went on to hold several key Kerala Cabinet Posts (Deputy Chief Minister, Minister for Education, [[Interior minister|Home Affairs Minister]], and Minister for Finance) under a number of Chief Ministers ([[E. M. S. Namboodiripad]], [[C. Achutha Menon]], [[K. Karunakaran]], [[A. K. Antony]], and [[P. K. Vasudevan Nair]]) in the following decades.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> In 1962 (1962 - 67) and in 1973 (1973-77), he was elected to the [[Parliament of India]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He was a Member in [[University of Kerala|Kerala University]] Senate and served as Chairman, Governing Body, [[National Institute of Technology Calicut|REC, Calicut]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nC. H. was born in 1927 at Atholi, in northern Kerala, to Payampunathil Ali Musliyar and Mariyumma.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>Miller, Roland. E., \"Mappila\" in \"The Encyclopedia of Islam\". Volume VI. E. J. Brill, Leiden. 1987. pp. 458-56.</ref> He co-founded the [[Muslim Students Federation]], or the M. S. F., while a school student  in [[Zamorin's Guruvayurappan College|Calicut Zamorin's College]]. He helped to receive [[Liaquat Ali Khan]] in 1945. C. H. joined the ''[[Chandrika (newspaper)|Chandrika]]'' newspaper, the official organ the Muslim League,<ref>Jeffrey, Robin. \"Politics, Women and Well-Being: How Kerala became a Model\" Palgrave McMillan (1992); 112 and 114.</ref> in 1946. Though only having Intermediate education, C. H. worked his way from Sub-Editor to the Editor of ''Chandrika'' by 1949.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>[http://niyamasabha.org/codes/Speakers%20&%20Deputy%20Speakers%20Book%20Final.pdf Speakers & Deputy Speakers Book \u2013 Kerala Legislative Assembly]</ref>\n\nC. H., who suffered from various health problems like [[diabetes]] and [[hypertension]], died suddenly of a massive [[brain hemorrhage]] at the State Institute of Medical Sciences in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] on 28 September, 1983, while serving as Deputy Chief Minister of Kerala. He was aged just 56 at the time of his death. His body was later taken to his native place, and was buried with full state honours.1<ref name=\":2\" /> He was survived by his mother, wife, three children - two daughters and a son, [[M. K. Muneer]], who later became a noted politician on his own right, and went on to serve as a minister in [[Third A. K. Antony ministry|A. K. Antony]] and [[Oommen Chandy]] ministries.\n\n{{quote box\n| width = 35em\n| bgcolor = #cef4c0\n| align = right\n| quote = \"Young men like C. H. Muhammad Koya realized that violent revolt promised nothing for them [the Kerala Muslims]. Electoral politics, on the other hand, might offer a great deal.\"\n| source = \u2014 '''Robin Jeffrey (historian)<ref>Jeffrey, Robin. \"Politics, Women and Well-Being: How Kerala became a Model\" Palgrave McMillan (1992); 112 and 114.</ref>\n}}\n\n== Career ==\n*[[List of chief ministers of Kerala|Chief Minister of Kerala]] - October 12 to December 1, 1979\n*[[List of Deputy Chief Ministers of Kerala|Deputy Chief Minister of Kerala]] \n** December 28, 1981 - March 17, 1982<ref name=\":1\" /> (2nd [[K. Karunakaran|Karunakaran]] Ministry)\n** May 24, 1982 - September 28, 1983<ref name=\":1\" /> (3rd [[K. Karunakaran|Karunakaran]] Ministry)\n* Speaker, 2nd [[Kerala Legislative Assembly]] \n**09-06-1961 to 10-11-1961<ref name=\":2\">[http://www.niyamasabha.org/codes/members/m424.htm Kerala Legislative Assembly]</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> ([[Pattom A. Thanu Pillai|Pattom]] Ministry)\n* Minister for Education \n**06-03-1967 to 21-10-1969<ref name=\":1\" /> (2nd [[E. M. S. Namboodiripad|E. M. S.]] Ministry)\n* Minister for Education and Home \n**01-11-1969 to 01-08-1970 (1st [[C. Achutha Menon|Achutha Menon]] Ministry)\n**04-10-1970 to 01-03-1973<ref name=\":1\" /> (2nd [[C. Achutha Menon|Achutha Menon]] Ministry)\n* Minister for Education\n**27-04-1977 to 20-12-1977 (1st [[A. K. Antony|Antony]] Ministry)\n**04-10-1978 to 27-10-1978 (1st [[A. K. Antony|Antony]] Ministry)\n**29-10-1978 to 07-10-1979<ref name=\":1\" /> ([[P. K. Vasudevan Nair|P. K. V.]] Ministry)\n* Minister for Finance and Education \n**25-03-1977 to 25-04-1977<ref name=\":1\" /> (1st [[K. Karunakaran|Karunakaran]] Ministry)\n\n* Member of Kerala Legislative Assembly<ref name=\":2\" />\n**1st Assembly (1957\u201359) - Tanur\n**2nd Assembly  (1960\u201364) - Tanur (resigned on 06 March 1962)<ref name=\":2\" />\n**3rd Assembly (1967\u201370) - Mankada\n**4th Assembly (1970\u201377) - Kondotti (resigned on 05 February 1973)<ref name=\":2\" />\n**5th Assembly  (1977\u201379) - Malappuram\n**6th Assembly (1980\u201382) - Manjeri\n**7th Assembly  (1982\u201387) - Manjeri\n\n== Legacy ==\nC. H. was known as a \"fiery and eloquent orator\" and was described by scholar R. E. Miller as \"grassroots star of the Mappila community\" and the \"ranking hero of Muslim youth\" in Kerala.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n* As the Minister of Education (Kerala), C. H. championed the progress of the Mappila community in secular education, but also advocated higher standards in the \"Arabic Colleges\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n* During C. H.'s tenure, the [[University of Calicut]] was established (in northern Kerala) 2nd EMS Govt..<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=TC6zCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA236#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Mappila Muslim Culture: How a Historic Muslim Community in India Has Blended Tradition and Modernity|last=Miller|first=Roland E.|date=2015-04-27|publisher=SUNY Press|year=|isbn=9781438456010|location=|pages=236|language=en}}</ref>\n* C. H. acted a \"bridge-builder\" among various social and religious groups of Kerala.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* C. H. is remembered for his \"spirited\" reply to [[Jawaharlal Nehru]], the [[Prime Minister of India]] (when the latter publicly criticized [[Indian Union Muslim League]] in 1955).<ref name=\":0\" />\n<br>\n{{wide image|Kerala Council of Ministers 1979 CH Mohammed Koya.jpg|700px|Kerala Council of Ministers, 1979, with C. H. Mohammad Koya}}\n\n== Works<ref name=\":2\" /> ==\n\n* ''My Haj pilgrimage''\n* ''Caux-London-Cairo''\n*''The Malaysia I Saw''\n* ''How Legislative Assembly Works''\n*''Soviet Union''\n*''Muslim Rule in India Through Stories''\n* ''Five Days in Sri Lanka''\n* ''Camel to Cadillac''\n*''Travel Around the world''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|C. H. Mohammed Koya}}\n*[https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/interview/story/19791130-rss-is-attacking-the-muslim-minority-mohammed-koya-822379-2014-02-21 C. H. Mohammad Koya: Interview (India Today) 1979]\n*[http://niyamasabha.org/codes/Speakers%20&%20Deputy%20Speakers%20Book%20Final.pdf Speakers & Deputy Speakers Book \u2013 Kerala Legislative Assembly]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before = [[P.K. Vasudevan Nair]] | title = [[Chief Minister of Kerala]] | years = 1979\u2013 1979 | after = [[E.K. Nayanar]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Seethi Sahib]] | title = [[Speaker (politics)|Speaker]] of [[Kerala Legislative Assembly]] | years = 1961\u2013 1961 | after =   Alexander Parambithara}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{United Democratic Front (Kerala)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koya, C. H. Mohammed}}\n[[Category:1927 births|Koya, C.H. Mohammed]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths|Koya, C.H. Mohammed]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Kerala]]\n[[Category:Malayali politicians]]\n[[Category:Kerala politicians]]\n[[Category:Malayali people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Kozhikode]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Kerala Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language writers]]\n[[Category:Indian Union Muslim League politicians]]\n[[Category:3rd Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Deputy chief ministers of Kerala]]\n[[Category:Kerala MLAs 1957\u20131959]]\n[[Category:Kerala MLAs 1960\u20131964]]\n[[Category:Education Ministers of Kerala]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toAtholi(link changed toAtholi, Kerala) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C._H._Mohammed_Koya"}
{"title_page": "Ted Eisenberg", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image       = Ted Eisenberg Plastic Surgeon.jpg\n| name        = Dr. Ted Eisenberg\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1952|6|21}}\n| residence   = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| occupation  = [[Plastic Surgeon]]\n| spouse      = Joyce Eisenberg (1973\u2013present)\n| children    = 2\n| website     = {{URL|http://lookingnatural.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Ted Eisenberg''' [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine|D.O.]] is a [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] based [[plastic surgeon]] who specializes in [[Plastic surgery#Cosmetic surgery|cosmetic]] breast surgery. He holds a [[Guinness World Record]] for the most [[breast augmentation]] surgeries performed in a lifetime (male){{mdash}} 3460.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metro.co.uk/weird/857966-record-breaking-breast-doctor-enjoys-knife-throwing-in-his-spare-time | title=Record-breaking breast doctor enjoys knife-throwing in his spare time | publisher=Metro.co.uk (Associated Newspapers Limited) | date=March 13, 2011 | accessdate=January 12, 2012 | author=Taylor, Joel}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldrecordacademy.com/society/most_breast_augmentation_surgeries_performed_Ted_Eisenberg_sets_world_record_112146.html | title=Most breast augmentation surgeries performed: Ted Eisenberg sets world record | publisher=Worldrecordacademy.com | date=March 7, 2011 | accessdate=January 15, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nEisenberg was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, the son of Martin (a graphic artist) and Mollie (a housewife), and graduated from [[Overbrook High School (Philadelphia)]]. He received a B.S. in pre-medicine from the [[Pennsylvania State University]] and graduated from the [[Philadelphia College of Osteopathic Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.healthgrades.com/physician/dr-ted-eisenberg-xwhnr/background-check  |title=Dr. Ted S. Eisenberg, DO |author= |year=2012 |work= |publisher=Health Grades, Inc |accessdate=21 September 2012}}</ref> He trained in General Surgery at Metropolitan Hospital and Plastic Surgery at Thomas Jefferson University, Albert Einstein Medical Center Northern Division and Hahnemann Hospital. He married Joyce Kirschner in 1973 and has a son, Benjamin, and a daughter, Samantha. \n\n==Career==\nMuch of Eisenberg's early work in the mid-1980s involved the use of [[tissue expansion]] for reconstructive surgery. He implanted tissue expanders for a total nasal reconstruction after cancer surgery; to repair a scalp that was scarred from shrapnel wounds incurred by a Marine during the [[Korean War]]; to build a breast for a young woman with [[Poland syndrome]]; and to expand a contracted eye socket in order to provide a silicone foundation as require for an [[Ocular prosthesis|acrylic eye prosthesis]].<ref>Detjen, Jim: \"Skin Repair Is Expanding: Soft Tissue Expansion Is Giving Hope to Victims of Cancer, Burns, Accidents and Birth Defects.\" The Philadelphia Inquirer,'' June 1988.</ref> <ref>Van Atta, Burr: \"It Was a Bit of a Stretch, But It Reversed His Baldness.\" The Philadelphia Inquirer,'' March 1989.</ref> Eisenberg's research on [[Dupuytren's contracture]] is published in a French monograph.<ref>LR. Tubiana, J.T. Hueston, eds. \"La Maladie de Dupuytren.\" Expansion Scientific Francaise, 1986: p. 210-213.</ref> For over a decade, he served on a national committee that evaluates the standards for plastic surgery residencies.<ref>''ACOS News'', Feb. 1994: Vol. 32 (4): p. 5.</ref> He was National Chairman of the Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery Division of the American College of Osteopathic Surgeons and served on the certifying board of the [[American Osteopathic Board of Surgery]] <ref>''Physician's News Digest'', May 1992, p. 19.</ref>\n\nSince 1999, Eisenberg has focused his practice solely on cosmetic breast surgery: [[augmentation mammoplasty]], [[mastopexy]] (breast lift), correction of breast asymmetry, and [[breast reduction]].<ref>[[Faye Flam|Flam, Faye]]. \"No End to the Quest for More Curves.\" ''Philadelphia Inquirer,'' Oct. 2005.</ref> He has contributed articles on the trade-offs between saline versus silicone [[breast implants]],<ref>Eisenberg, Ted S. \u201cSilicone Gel Implants are Back: So What?\u201d ''American Journal of Cosmetic Surgery'' March 2009: 26 (1): 5-7.,</ref> a new one-stage approach to correcting tuberous breast deformity with saline implants, <ref>Eisenberg, Ted S. \u201cOne-Stage Correction of Tuberous Breast Deformity Using Saline Implants: Without the Need for Radial Scoring or Lowering the Inframammary Fold \u201d ''American Journal of Cosmetic Surgery'' April 2019: https://doi.org/10.1177/0748806819841466.</ref> minimizing post-operative nausea and vomiting,<ref>Eisenberg, Ted S. \u201cBreast Augmentation: Minimizing Post-Operative Nausea and Vomiting (PONV), Maximizing Patient Satisfaction\u201d ''American Journal of Cosmetic Surgery'' Dec. 2008: 25 (4): 264-267.</ref> and a novel use of the StratticeTM patch for breast implant exposure.<ref>Eisenberg, Ted S. \u201cImplant Exposure Through a Breast Augmentation Incision Repaired with Porcine Acellular Dermal Matrix (StratticeTM): A Technique to Ensure Graft Take\u201d ''Aesthetic Plastic Surgery.'' Aug. 2011: 35: (4): 681-683.</ref> An authority on simultaneous augmentation mastopexy,<ref>Drew, Eliza. \"Aesthetic Exchange: Surgeons Discuss Simultaneous Augmentation Mastopexy Versus Staged Approach.\u201d \u201cCosmetic Surgery Times,'' April 1, 2012.</ref> Eisenberg is the creator of the IDEAL Breast Lift,<ref>Eisenberg, Ted S. \"Ideal Breast Lift Augmentation Mastopexy for Moderately to Severely Ptotic Breasts: Previsualizing Breast Shape and Symmetry With an Innovative and Versatile Stapling Technique.\" ''American Journal of Cosmetic Surgery.'' Sept. 2009: 26 (3): 168-176.</ref> a technique to previsualize the extent of tissue to be removed to achieve symmetry and maximum lift.<ref>Eisenberg, Ted. S. \"Simultaneous Augmentation Mastopexy: A Technique for Maximum En Bloc Skin Resection Using the Inverted-T Pattern Regardless of Implant Size, Asymmetry, or Ptosis.\" ''Aesthetic Plastic Surgery.'' April 2012: 36: (2): 349-354.</ref><ref>Shiffman, Melvin A., and Alberto Di Giuseppe, eds. \"Cosmetic Surgery: Art and Techniques.\" Springer, 2012: Chapter 39: 605-620.</ref> He teaches his technique to surgeons around the country. Eisenberg was named a Fellow in the American College of Osteopathic Surgeons and is an associate professor of surgery at Philadelphia College of Osteopathic Medicine.\n\n==Awards and community contributions==\nIn 1993, Dr. Eisenberg was nominated for the Knight Legion of Goodness Award by the Italian-American Press.<ref>\u201cHighly Deserving Citizens Nominated for the Knights Legion of Goodness.\u201d ''Philadelphia Exclusive,''  Oct. 6, 1993.</ref> In 2009, Dr. Eisenberg achieved a Guinness World Record for the most breast augmentation surgeries performed in a lifetime (male){{mdash}} 3,460.<ref name=\"avinterview\" /> With Joyce K. Eisenberg, he co-authored ''The Scoop on Breasts: A Plastic Surgeon Busts the Myths'', in 2012.<ref name=\"avinterview\">{{cite web|title=Dr. Ted Eisenberg and Joyce K. Eisenberg about \"The Scoop on Breasts: A Plastic Surgeon Busts the Myths\"|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xmdDTu3Hcf0|work=A&E Author Interviews|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=2 September 2013|author=Marc Greece|format=audiovisual|date=12 June 2013|quote=Dr. Eisenberg, who holds the Guinness World Record for most breast augmentations performed in a lifetime, candidly answers more than 200 actual patient questions [in his book] The Scoop on Breasts...}}</ref> Dr. Eisenberg is a corporate sponsor of the [[Linda Creed]] Breast Cancer Foundation, whose core program is to provide free [[mammograms]] for women with little or no medical insurance.\n\n==Hobbies==\nA tournament [[knife thrower]], Eisenberg is a member of the International Knife Throwers Hall of Fame and is ranked 18th in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=World Knife and Tomahawk Rankings|url=http://www.ikthof.com/rankings.html|work=IKTHOF|publisher=International Knife Throwers Hall of Fame|accessdate=2 September 2013|quote=IKTHOF World Expert Division Rankings in Knife Throwing... 18. Dr. Ted Eisenberg}}</ref> In 2009, he participated in his first [[tomahawk (axe)]] throwing competition; he is the 2018 world champion in the long distance tomahawk competition.<ref>Carey, Art: \"Nip & Duck: Surgeon's Cool Hobby Is Throwing Knives at Targets.\" The Philadelphia Inquirer,'' July 2009.</ref><ref>Apgar, Blake: \"Amateurs, pros let blades fly at knife-throwing contest in Las Vegas.\" Las Vegas Review-Journal,'' April 9, 2017.</ref><ref>Croatto, Pet: \"Knife-Throwing as a Sport: Who Would Have Thunk It?.\" The New York Times,'' Sept. 2017.</ref> He is also an amateur [[ballroom dance]]r; he and his wife competed in a pre-show event during a \"Dancing With the Stars\" tour.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lookingnatural.com Dr. Ted Eisenberg]\n* [http://www.facos.org American College of Osteopathic Surgeons]\n* [http://www.thescooponbreasts.com The Scoop on Breasts]\n* [http://www.lindacreed.org/get-involved/corporate-community-partners Linda Creed Breast Cancer Foundation]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eisenberg, Ted}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American plastic surgeons]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia College of Osteopathic Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Philadelphia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image       = Ted Eisenberg Plastic Surgeon.jpg\n| name        = Dr. Ted Eisenberg\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1952|6|21}}\n| residence   = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| occupation  = [[Plastic Surgeon]]\n| spouse      = Joyce Eisenberg (1973\u2013present)\n| children    = 2\n| website     = {{URL|http://lookingnatural.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Ted Eisenberg''' [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine|D.O.]] is a [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] based [[plastic surgeon]] who specializes in [[Plastic surgery#Cosmetic surgery|cosmetic]] breast surgery. He holds a [[Guinness World Record]] for the most [[breast augmentation]] surgeries performed in a lifetime (male){{mdash}} 3460.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metro.co.uk/weird/857966-record-breaking-breast-doctor-enjoys-knife-throwing-in-his-spare-time | title=Record-breaking breast doctor enjoys knife-throwing in his spare time | publisher=Metro.co.uk (Associated Newspapers Limited) | date=March 13, 2011 | accessdate=January 12, 2012 | author=Taylor, Joel}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldrecordacademy.com/society/most_breast_augmentation_surgeries_performed_Ted_Eisenberg_sets_world_record_112146.html | title=Most breast augmentation surgeries performed: Ted Eisenberg sets world record | publisher=Worldrecordacademy.com | date=March 7, 2011 | accessdate=January 15, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nEisenberg was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, the son of Martin (a graphic artist) and Mollie (a housewife), and graduated from [[Overbrook High School (Philadelphia)]]. He received a B.S. in pre-medicine from the [[Pennsylvania State University]] and graduated from the [[Philadelphia College of Osteopathic Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.healthgrades.com/physician/dr-ted-eisenberg-xwhnr/background-check  |title=Dr. Ted S. Eisenberg, DO |author= |year=2012 |work= |publisher=Health Grades, Inc |accessdate=21 September 2012}}</ref> He trained in General Surgery at Metropolitan Hospital and Plastic Surgery at Thomas Jefferson University, Albert Einstein Medical Center Northern Division and Hahnemann Hospital. He married Joyce Kirschner in 1973 and has a son, Benjamin, and a daughter, Samantha. \n\n==Career==\nMuch of Eisenberg's early work in the mid-1980s involved the use of [[tissue expansion]] for reconstructive surgery. He implanted tissue expanders for a total nasal reconstruction after cancer surgery; to repair a scalp that was scarred from shrapnel wounds incurred by a Marine during the [[Korean War]]; to build a breast for a young woman with [[Poland syndrome]]; and to expand a contracted eye socket in order to provide a silicone foundation as require for an [[Ocular prosthesis|acrylic eye prosthesis]].<ref>Detjen, Jim: \"Skin Repair Is Expanding: Soft Tissue Expansion Is Giving Hope to Victims of Cancer, Burns, Accidents and Birth Defects.\" The Philadelphia Inquirer,'' June 1988.</ref> <ref>Van Atta, Burr: \"It Was a Bit of a Stretch, But It Reversed His Baldness.\" The Philadelphia Inquirer,'' March 1989.</ref> Eisenberg's research on [[Dupuytren's contracture]] is published in a French monograph.<ref>LR. Tubiana, J.T. Hueston, eds. \"La Maladie de Dupuytren.\" Expansion Scientific Francaise, 1986: p. 210-213.</ref> For over a decade, he served on a national committee that evaluates the standards for plastic surgery residencies.<ref>''ACOS News'', Feb. 1994: Vol. 32 (4): p. 5.</ref> He was National Chairman of the Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery Division of the American College of Osteopathic Surgeons and served on the certifying board of the [[American Osteopathic Board of Surgery]] <ref>''Physician's News Digest'', May 1992, p. 19.</ref>\n\nSince 1999, Eisenberg has focused his practice solely on cosmetic breast surgery: [[augmentation mammoplasty]], [[mastopexy]] (breast lift), correction of breast asymmetry, and [[breast reduction]].<ref>[[Faye Flam|Flam, Faye]]. \"No End to the Quest for More Curves.\" ''Philadelphia Inquirer,'' Oct. 2005.</ref> He has contributed articles on the trade-offs between saline versus silicone [[breast implants]],<ref>Eisenberg, Ted S. \u201cSilicone Gel Implants are Back: So What?\u201d ''American Journal of Cosmetic Surgery'' March 2009: 26 (1): 5-7.,</ref> a new one-stage approach to correcting tuberous breast deformity with saline implants, <ref>Eisenberg, Ted S. \u201cOne-Stage Correction of Tuberous Breast Deformity Using Saline Implants: Without the Need for Radial Scoring or Lowering the Inframammary Fold \u201d ''American Journal of Cosmetic Surgery'' April 2019: https://doi.org/10.1177/0748806819841466.</ref> minimizing post-operative nausea and vomiting,<ref>Eisenberg, Ted S. \u201cBreast Augmentation: Minimizing Post-Operative Nausea and Vomiting (PONV), Maximizing Patient Satisfaction\u201d ''American Journal of Cosmetic Surgery'' Dec. 2008: 25 (4): 264-267.</ref> and a novel use of the StratticeTM patch for breast implant exposure.<ref>Eisenberg, Ted S. \u201cImplant Exposure Through a Breast Augmentation Incision Repaired with Porcine Acellular Dermal Matrix (StratticeTM): A Technique to Ensure Graft Take\u201d ''Aesthetic Plastic Surgery.'' Aug. 2011: 35: (4): 681-683.</ref> An authority on simultaneous augmentation mastopexy,<ref>Drew, Eliza. \"Aesthetic Exchange: Surgeons Discuss Simultaneous Augmentation Mastopexy Versus Staged Approach.\u201d \u201cCosmetic Surgery Times,'' April 1, 2012.</ref> Eisenberg is the creator of the IDEAL Breast Lift,<ref>Eisenberg, Ted S. \"Ideal Breast Lift Augmentation Mastopexy for Moderately to Severely Ptotic Breasts: Previsualizing Breast Shape and Symmetry With an Innovative and Versatile Stapling Technique.\" ''American Journal of Cosmetic Surgery.'' Sept. 2009: 26 (3): 168-176.</ref> a technique to previsualize the extent of tissue to be removed to achieve symmetry and maximum lift.<ref>Eisenberg, Ted. S. \"Simultaneous Augmentation Mastopexy: A Technique for Maximum En Bloc Skin Resection Using the Inverted-T Pattern Regardless of Implant Size, Asymmetry, or Ptosis.\" ''Aesthetic Plastic Surgery.'' April 2012: 36: (2): 349-354.</ref><ref>Shiffman, Melvin A., and Alberto Di Giuseppe, eds. \"Cosmetic Surgery: Art and Techniques.\" Springer, 2012: Chapter 39: 605-620.</ref> He teaches his technique to surgeons around the country. Eisenberg was named a Fellow in the American College of Osteopathic Surgeons and is an associate professor of surgery at Philadelphia College of Osteopathic Medicine.\n\n==Awards and community contributions==\nIn 1993, Dr. Eisenberg was nominated for the Knight Legion of Goodness Award by the Italian-American Press.<ref>\u201cHighly Deserving Citizens Nominated for the Knights Legion of Goodness.\u201d ''Philadelphia Exclusive,''  Oct. 6, 1993.</ref> In 2009, Dr. Eisenberg achieved a Guinness World Record for the most breast augmentation surgeries performed in a lifetime (male){{mdash}} 3,460.<ref name=\"avinterview\" /> With Joyce K. Eisenberg, he co-authored ''The Scoop on Breasts: A Plastic Surgeon Busts the Myths'', in 2012.<ref name=\"avinterview\">{{cite web|title=Dr. Ted Eisenberg and Joyce K. Eisenberg about \"The Scoop on Breasts: A Plastic Surgeon Busts the Myths\"|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xmdDTu3Hcf0|work=A&E Author Interviews|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=2 September 2013|author=Marc Greece|format=audiovisual|date=12 June 2013|quote=Dr. Eisenberg, who holds the Guinness World Record for most breast augmentations performed in a lifetime, candidly answers more than 200 actual patient questions [in his book] The Scoop on Breasts...}}</ref> Dr. Eisenberg is a corporate sponsor of the [[Linda Creed]] Breast Cancer Foundation, whose core program is to provide free [[mammograms]] for women with little or no medical insurance.\n\n==Hobbies==\nA tournament [[knife thrower]], Eisenberg is a member of the International Knife Throwers Hall of Fame and is ranked 18th in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=World Knife and Tomahawk Rankings|url=http://www.ikthof.com/rankings.html|work=IKTHOF|publisher=International Knife Throwers Hall of Fame|accessdate=2 September 2013|quote=IKTHOF World Expert Division Rankings in Knife Throwing... 18. Dr. Ted Eisenberg}}</ref> In 2009, he participated in his first [[tomahawk (axe)]] throwing competition; he is the 2018 world champion in the long distance tomahawk competition.<ref>Carey, Art: \"Nip & Duck: Surgeon's Cool Hobby Is Throwing Knives at Targets.\" The Philadelphia Inquirer,'' July 2009.</ref><ref>Apgar, Blake: \"Amateurs, pros let blades fly at knife-throwing contest in Las Vegas.\" Las Vegas Review-Journal,'' April 9, 2017.</ref><ref>Croatto, Pet: \"Knife-Throwing as a Sport: Who Would Have Thunk It?.\" The New York Times,'' Sept. 2017.</ref> He is also an amateur [[ballroom dance]]r; he and his wife competed in a pre-show event during a \"Dancing With the Stars\" tour.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lookingnatural.com Dr. Ted Eisenberg]\n* [http://www.facos.org American College of Osteopathic Surgeons]\n* [http://www.thescooponbreasts.com The Scoop on Breasts]\n* [http://www.lindacreed.org/screenings.php Linda Creed Breast Cancer Foundation]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eisenberg, Ted}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American plastic surgeons]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia College of Osteopathic Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Philadelphia]]\n", "name_user": "Joycejanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ted_Eisenberg"}
{"title_page": "List of Colorado College people", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe following is a '''list of notable people associated with [[Colorado College]]''', located in the American city of [[Colorado Springs]], [[Colorado]].\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\n===Arts===\n====Film, theatre, and broadcasting====\n* [[Neal Baer]], television producer/writer and pediatrician\n* [[Dee Bradley Baker]], voice actor\n* [[Robert Bogue]], actor \n* [[Ken Curtis]], singer and actor best known for his role as Festus Haggen on the long-running [[CBS]] [[western (genre)|western]] television series ''[[Gunsmoke]]''\n* [[Jim Dziura]], film director, cinematographer, and editor\n* Nancy Nagel Gibbs, Broadway producer, co-founder of 321 Theatrical Management, recipient of the [[Lucille Lortel Award]]\n* [[Daniel Junge]], [[Academy Award]]-winning documentary filmmaker (''[[Saving Face (2012 film)|Saving Face]]'')\n* [[Cynthia Lowen]], documentary filmmaker (''[[Bully (2011 film)|Bully]]'')\n* [[Peter Mortimer (filmmaker)|Peter Mortimer]], Sports Emmy-winning filmmaker, co-founder of the REEL ROCK Film Tour\n* [[Arden Myrin]], comedian and actress\n* [[Doug Pray]], Emmy Award-winning film director (''[[Art & Copy]]'')\n* [[Derek Richardson (actor)|Derek Richardson]], actor\n* [[Nick Rosen (filmmaker)|Nick Rosen]], filmmaker, co-creator of the Emmy-nominated<ref>{{cite web|last=Byrne|first=Christopher|title=The 2011 Sports EMMY Nominations are Here|url=http://www.eyeonsportsmedia.com/2011/03/2011-sports-emmy-award-nominations-are.html|publisher=The Cayuga Group, LLC|accessdate=19 March 2012}}</ref> National Geographic series, First Ascent\n* [[Steve Sabol]], film producer and former president of [[NFL Films]]\n* Timothy J. Sexton,<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0786694/ Timothy J. Sexton - IMDb<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Academy Award nominated screenwriter for film (''[[Children of Men]]'') and television\n* [[Aaron Shure]], Emmy Award-winning television writer, director, and producer (''[[Everybody Loves Raymond]]'', ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'')\n* [[Marc Webb]], producer and director of music videos and films such as ''[[(500) Days of Summer]]'' and ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]''\n* [[Dean Winters]], actor\n\n====Writers, journalists and publishers====\n* [[David Burnett (photojournalist)|David Burnett]], photojournalist recognized for the [[World Press Photo of the Year]] (1980), co-recipient of the [[Robert Capa Gold Medal]], and named Magazine Photographer of the Year by the [[National Press Photographers Association]]\n* Vincent Bzdek,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.macmillan.com/author/vincentbzdek |title=Vincent Bzdek &#124; Authors &#124; Macmillan |publisher=Us.macmillan.com |date=2009-12-04 |accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref> news editor of ''The Washington Post'', author of ''Woman of the House'' and ''The Kennedy Legacy''\n* [[Michael Dahlie]], novelist\n* [[Gregg Easterbrook]], writer and contributing editor of ''[[The New Republic]]'' and ''[[The Atlantic Monthly]]''\n* [[Frieda Ekotto]], francophone African woman novelist and literary critic\n* [[Thomas Hornsby Ferril]], poet laureate of Colorado\n* [[Mark Fiore]], [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning political cartoonist\n* [[Edward K. Gaylord]], publisher of the ''Daily Oklahoman''\n* [[Kaui Hart Hemmings]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kqed.org/arts/literature/article.jsp?essid=17160 |title=Kaui Hart Hemmings: The Descendants: Literature &#124; KQED Public Media for Northern CA |publisher=Kqed.org |date=2007-06-19 |accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref> novelist, author of ''[[The Descendants (novel)|The Descendants]]'' and ''House of Thieves''\n* [[Mabel Barbee Lee]], writer\n* Thom Shanker,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/people/s/thom_shanker/index.html?inline=nyt-per | work=The New York Times | title=People: Thom Shanker}}</ref> Pentagon correspondent at ''The New York Times''\n\n====Artists and musicians====\n* [[Herbert Beattie]], operatic bass and voice teacher\n* [[Eric Bransby]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tfaoi.com/aa/4aa/4aa414.htm |title=Eric Bransby: Draftsman and Muralist; essay by William Underwood Eiland |publisher=Tfaoi.com |date=2004-07-25 |accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref> muralist\n* [[Cecil Effinger]], composer, oboist, and inventor\n* [[Jo Estill]], singer, singing voice specialist and voice researcher\n* [[Glenna Goodacre]], sculptor\n* [[Margaret Kilgallen]], [[Mission School]] artist and printmaker\n* [[Janet Maguire]], composer\n* [[Max Morath]], ragtime pianist, composer, actor and author\n* [[Ann Royer]], painter, sculptor\n* [[Abigail Washburn]], [[Grammy Award]]-winning banjo player and singer\n\n===Economics and business===\n*[[Obadiah J. Barker]], founder and president of Barker Brothers\n* [[Charles Cicchetti]], co-founder Madison Consulting Group, Professor of Economics at the University of Southern California\n* [[Harold Thayer Davis]], mathematician, statistician, and econometrician, known for the [[Davis distribution]]\n* [[Randall Edwards (politician)|Randall Edwards]], State Treasurer of Oregon\n* [[Alexander Ellis III]], partner in the venture-capital firm Rockport Capital Partners\n* [[Joe Ellis]], President of the [[Denver Broncos]]\n* [[James Heckman]], winner of 2000 [[Nobel Prize for Economics]], Henry Schultz Distinguished Service Professor of Economics at the [[University of Chicago]], Professor of Law at [[University of Chicago Law School|the Law School]], and director of the [https://cehd.uchicago.edu/ Center for the Economics of Human Development]\n* [[David Malpass]], President of the [[World Bank]]\n* Adam F. Press, former Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of The St. John Companies, Inc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=51873336&privcapId=8034367&previousCapId=8034367&previousTitle=The%20St.%20John%20Companies,%20Inc.|website=BusinessWeek|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n* [[Sebastian Suhl]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gay |first=Sara |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601085&sid=apfJ2j2Abk3A |title=Prada Says It Isn't in Talks to Sell Stake Amid Buyout Interest |publisher=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] |date=2009-06-12 |accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref> former COO of [[Prada]] S.p.A.; CEO at [[Givenchy]]<ref name=\"Givenchy Looks to Capitalize on Momentum\">{{cite web | url=http://www.wwd.com/retail-news/designer-luxury/givenchy-looks-to-capitalize-on-momentum-7266346?src=nl/mornReport/20131107 | title=Givenchy Looks to Capitalize on Momentum | publisher=WWD | date=7 November 2013 | accessdate=7 November 2013 | author=Socha, Miles}}</ref>\n* [[Amy Tucker (game designer)|Amy Tucker]], inventor of [[Xeko]]\n\n===Government and politics===\n* [[Elizabeth Cheney]], [[U.S. Representative]] for Wyoming\n* [[Lynne Cheney]], wife of former Vice President Dick Cheney, novelist, conservative scholar, and former talk-show host\n* [[Mary Cheney]], former campaign aide, daughter of former Vice President [[Dick Cheney]] and [[Lynne Cheney]]\n* [[Matt Claman]], former acting mayor of Anchorage, Alaska\n* [[Marian W. Clarke]], former member U.S. House of Representatives\n* [[Diana DeGette]], U.S. House of Representatives, attorney\n* [[Myron Ebell]], Director of Global Warming and International Environmental Policy at the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]]\n* [[Lori Garver]], deputy NASA administrator\n* [[Abdul Aziz Abdul Ghani]], former prime minister of Yemen\n* [[Harrison Loesch]], former Assistant Secretary of Interior\n* [[Helen Stevenson Meyner]], former member U.S. House of Representatives\n* [[Ted Morton]], politician\n* [[Michael Nava]], attorney and writer\n* [[Mark Norris (judge)|Mark Norris]], Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Tennessee]]\n* [[Philip Perry]], attorney, former acting associate attorney general at Department of Justice, former general counsel of Office of Management and Budget, and former general counsel of Department of Homeland Security\n* [[Gregor Robertson (politician)|Gregor Robertson]], mayor of Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada\n* [[Ken Salazar]], United States Secretary of the Interior, former United States senator\n* [[Harry H. Seldomridge]], former U.S. Representative from Colorado\n* [[Joe Simitian]], California politician\n* [[Colin M. Simpson]], former House Speaker of the [[Wyoming House of Representatives]]\n* [[Richard H. Stallings]], politician\n* [[Stuart Stevens]], strategist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tnr.com/article/magazine/politics/105738/stuart-stevens-romney-strategist-interesting |title=The Square and the Flair |work=[[The New Republic]] |date=August 2, 2012 |accessdate=September 23, 2012|first=Noam|last=Scheiber}}</ref> for [[Mitt Romney presidential campaign, 2012|Mitt Romney's 2012 presidential campaign]], cofounder of Washington, D.C.\u2009-\u2009based political media consultancy Stevens & Schriefer Group\n* [[Timothy Tymkovich]], [[federal judge]] on the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit]]\n\n===Academia===\n* [[William Drea Adams]], former President, [[Colby College]] and [[Bucknell University]]\n* [[Anne Basting]], winner of 2016 [[MacArthur Fellowship]], Professor of Theater at the [[University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee]]\n* Frank O. Bowman III, Floyd R. Gibson Professor of Law at the [[University of Missouri Law School]], leading scholar of the history and law of impeachment and of federal criminal sentencing<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://law.missouri.edu/person/frank-o-bowman-iii/|title=Frank O. Bowman III|newspaper=law.missouri.edu|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Charles L. Briggs]], [[Alan Dundes]] Distinguished Professor of Folklore at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n* [[Frieda Ekotto]], Professor of French, Comparative Literature, Afroamerican and African Studies at the [[University of Michigan]]\n* [[Paul Franco]], professor of government at [[Bowdoin College]]\n* [[Donna Haraway]], prominent scholar in the field of science and technology studies\n* [[James Heckman]], winner of 2000 [[Nobel Prize for Economics]], Henry Schultz Distinguished Service Professor of Economics at the [[University of Chicago]] and director of the [https://cehd.uchicago.edu/ Center for the Economics of Human Development]\n* [[Huntington D. Lambert]], dean of the [[Harvard Division of Continuing Education|Division of Continuing Education]] and [[Harvard Extension School|University Extension]] at [[Harvard University]]\n* [[Liang Shih-chiu]], academic single-handedly responsible for translating the works of William Shakespeare into Chinese\n* [[Reginald McKnight]], [[Hamilton Holmes]] Professor of English at the [[University of Georgia]]\n* [[John Novembre]], winner of 2015 [[MacArthur Fellowship]], Professor of Computational Biology at the [[University of Chicago]]\n* [[Pauline Turner Strong]], director of the Humanities Institute at the [[University of Texas at Austin]]\n* Elmo Scott Watson, Professor of Journalism at [[Northwestern University]] (1924-1950)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mms.newberry.org/xml/xml_files/watson.xml|title=Elmo Scott Watson|newspaper=mms.newberry.org|access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Terry Winograd]], Professor of Computer Science at [[Stanford University]] and co-director of the Stanford Human-Computer Interaction Group\n\n===Science===\n*[[Sarah Andrews (author)|Sarah Andrews]], geologist and author\n*[[Brian J. Enquist]], Biologist and Ecologist\n* [[Richard Green (telecommunication)|Richard Green]], chairman of the Space Sciences Institute, previously served as President and CEO of [[CableLabs]]\n* [[Myra Keen]], malacologist and invertebrate paleontologist\n* [[Frank Leverett]], geologist who specialised in glaciology\n* [[Jane Lubchenco]], marine ecologist and environmental scientist, former NOAA Administrator\n* [[Marcia McNutt]], <small>[[Foreign Member of the Royal Society|ForMemRS]]</small>, is an [[United States|American]] [[Geophysics|geophysicist]] and the 22nd president of the [[National Academy of Sciences]] of the [[United States]] (NAS). She is the former [[editor-in-chief]] of ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'', the 15th director of the [[United States Geological Survey]] (USGS) (and first woman to hold the post), and science adviser to the [[United States Secretary of the Interior]].\n* [[Kenneth N. Ogle]], scientist of human vision\n* [[Andrew Spielman]], [[public health]] [[entomologist]]\n* [[G. Harry Stine]], founding figure of model rocketry, science and technology writer\n* [[William A. Welch]], engineer and environmentalist\n\n===Military===\n* [[Austin R. Brunelli]], Brigadier general in the Marine Corps, World War II [[Navy Cross]] recipient\n* [[Marcellus H. Chiles]], World War I [[Medal of Honor]] recipient\n* [[Bert Stiles]], World War II fighter pilot awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] and the [[Air Medal]]\n* [[Robert M. Stillman]], [[Major General]] in the [[United States Air Force]]\n\n===Athletics===\n\n====Olympics====\n''As of the [[2014 Winter Olympics]], 20 Colorado College students have competed in the Olympic Games, claiming a total of six medals (three golds, two silvers, one bronze).''\n\n* [[Trevor Barron]], race walker who competed at the 2012 Summer Olympics\n* Dan Dickison, sailor who competed as an alternate for the U.S. Virgin Islands Yachting Team at the 1984 Summer Olympics\n* [[Scott Driggers]], handballer, [[1988 Summer Olympics]]\n* [[Alison Dunlap]], professional cyclist, former Olympian\n* [[Peggy Fleming]], 1968 Olympic gold medalist in figure skating, three-time world champion figure skater (1966-1968)\n* [[Martina Franko]], Canada Women's Soccer Team, [[2008 Summer Olympics]]\n* [[Christine Haigler]], U.S. figure skater [[1964 Winter Olympics]]\n* [[David Jenkins (figure skater)|David Jenkins]], 1960 Olympic gold medalist in men's figure skating, three-time world champion (1957-1959)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/je/david-jenkins-2.html}}</ref>\n* [[Hayes Alan Jenkins]], [[Olympic medal|gold medalist]] in men's figure skating, [[1956 Winter Olympics]], four-time world champion figure skater (1953-1956)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/je/hayes-alan-jenkins-1.html}}</ref>\n* [[Tara Nott]], [[Olympic medal|gold medalist]] in women's [[Olympic weightlifting|weight lifting]], [[2000 Olympics]]<ref name=\"coloradocollege.edu\">{{cite web\n   |url=http://www.coloradocollege.edu/basics/aftercc/\n   |accessdate=2012-02-29\n   |title=After CC \u2022 Colorado College\n   |publisher=Colorado College\n   }}</ref>\n* [[Eliza Outtrim]], U.S. Freestyle Skiing team, [[2014 Winter Olympics]]\n* [[Hillary Wolf]], U.S. Judo Team, [[1996 Summer Olympics]] and [[2000 Summer Olympics]]\n\n====Football====\n* [[Dutch Clark]], [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] player and coach\n* [[John Gagliardi]], former football coach, [[College Football Hall of Fame]] inductee\n* [[Douglas Mitchell]], [[Canadian Football League]] player and [[Canadian Football League#League commissioners|commissioner]]\n* [[Ed Smith (defensive end)|Ed Smith]], former defensive end for the [[Denver Broncos]]\n\n====Hockey====\n''Over 170 Colorado College alumni have gone on to play professionally, including over 30 current and former NHL players. In addition, nine Colorado College alumni have represented their country in hockey at the Olympics.''<ref name=\"alumni\">{{cite web|work=Internet Hockey Database|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/alumni.php?tmi=5308|title=Alumni Report|year=2011|accessdate=May 11, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"alumni2013\">{{cite web|title=Tiger Hockey Media Guide 2013-2014|url=http://www.cctigers.com/documents/2013/10/19/2013-14_Media_Guide.pdf|accessdate=November 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n* [[Ryan Bach]], NHL goaltender\n* [[Richard Bachman (ice hockey)|Richard Bachman]], NHL player\n* [[Art Berglund]], ice hockey coach and executive, [[Lester Patrick Trophy]] award winner\n*[[Rick Boh]]\n*[[Colin Chisholm (ice hockey)|Colin Chisholm]]\n* [[Brian Connelly]], [[American Hockey League]] defenseman\n*[[Joey Crabb]], NHL winger, [[Florida Panthers]]\n* [[Dave Feamster]]\n*[[Bill Hay]], former [[Chicago Blackhawks]] centre\n* [[Jack Hillen]], NHL ice hockey defenceman, [[Nashville Predators]]\n*[[Doug Lidster]], NHL defencemen, member of Team Canada at the [[1984 Winter Olympics]]\n*[[Curtis McElhinney]]\n*[[Doug Palazzari]], [[United States Hockey Hall of Fame]] inductee\n*[[Toby Petersen]], right winger, [[Dallas Stars]]\n* [[Tom Preissing (ice hockey)|Tom Preissing]], NHL player, [[Hobey Baker Award]] finalist\n* [[Nate Prosser]]\n* [[Jaden Schwartz]], NHL [[St. Louis Blues]] forward, Captain Team Canada World Junior 2012\n* [[Peter Sejna]], NHL ice hockey center, [[2003 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships]] bronze medalist, [[Hobey Baker Award]] winner<ref name=\"hobeybaker.com\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.hobeybakeraward.com/page/show/219237-2003-peter-sejna\n |accessdate  = 2012-02-29\n |title       = 2003 - Peter Sejna <nowiki>|</nowiki> Past Winners\n |publisher   = Hobey Baker Memorial Award Foundation\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120610115843/http://www.hobeybakeraward.com/page/show/219237-2003-peter-sejna\n |archivedate = 2012-06-10\n}}</ref>\n* [[Marty Sertich]], AHL ice hockey center, [[Hobey Baker Award]] winner<ref name=\"hobeybaker.com\"/>\n* [[Brett Sterling]], NHL ice hockey player\n* [[Colin Stuart (ice hockey)|Colin Stuart]]\n* [[Mark Stuart (ice hockey)|Mark Stuart]]\n* [[Mike Stuart]], alternate captain, [[Winnipeg Jets]]\n* [[Brian Swanson]]\n* [[Lee Sweatt]]\n\n===Other===\n* [[Carol Rymer Davis]], 2004 [[Gordon Bennett Cup (ballooning)|Gordon Bennet Cup]] winner\n* [[Anton Krupicka]], ultra-runner, two-time [[Leadville 100]] winner\n* [[Bert Stiles]], pilot and author\n* [[Jerry Wainwright]], former Director of Basketball Operations for the [[Marquette Golden Eagles]]\n\n==Presidents of Colorado College==\nColorado College has had about 16 presidents and acting presidents since its founding:<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://coloradocollege.edu/library/SpecialCollections/Presidents.html\n |accessdate  = 2012-02-29\n |title       = Presidents of Colorado College\n |publisher   = Special Collections, Tutt Library\n |date        = August 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110716023845/http://www.coloradocollege.edu/library/SpecialCollections/Presidents.html\n |archivedate = 2011-07-16\n}}</ref>\n* Rev. Jonathan Edwards, 1874-1875<ref name=College_Yearbook_1897>{{cite book\n   |url=https://archive.org/stream/collegeyearbooka00emer/collegeyearbooka00emer_djvu.txt\n   |accessdate=2012-02-29\n   |title=The College year-book and athletic record for the academic year 1896-97\n   |editor=Edwin Emerson, Jr.\n   |location=New York\n   |publisher=Stone & Kimball\n}}</ref>\n* Rev. [[James G. Dougherty]], 1875-1876<ref name=College_Yearbook_1897/>\n* [[Edward P. Tenney]], 1876-1884\n* [[William F. Slocum]], Jr., 1888-1917<ref name=College_Yearbook_1897/>\n* [[Clyde A. Duniway]], 1917-1924\n*[[Charles Christopher Mierow]] - 1923-24 (acting) and 1925-1934\n* [[Charles Brown Hershey]], 1933-1934 (acting) and 1943-1945 (acting)\n* [[Thurston J. Davies]], 1934-1948\n* [[William H. Gill]], 1949-1955\n* [[Louis T. Benezet]], 1955-1963\n* [[Lloyd E. Worner]], 1963-1981\n* [[Thomas Cronin]], 1991 (acting)\n* [[Gresham Riley]], 1981-1992\n* [[Michael Grace (pianist)|Michael Grace]], 1992-1993 (acting)\n* [[Kathryn Mohrman]], 1993-2002\n* [[Richard F. Celeste]], 2002-2011\n* [[Jill Tiefenthaler]], 2011-present\n\n==Professors==\n* [[Ofer Ben-Amots]], [[Israeli-American]] [[classical composer]]\n* [[Rebecca Barnes]], environmental scientist, women-in-science activist, board member for [https://eswnonline.org/welcome/who-we-are/ Earth Science Women\u2019s Network] (ESWN)\n* Peter Blasenheim, Latin American historian, Brazilianist<ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.coloradocollege.edu/academics/dept/history/people/profile.dot?person=blasenheim_peter\n  |accessdate=2012-02-29\n  |title=Profile \u2022 History \u2022 Colorado College\n  |publisher=Colorado College\n  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www2.coloradocollege.edu/dept/hy/Faculty/Blasenheim.html \n |accessdate=2012-02-29 \n |title=Peter Blasenheim \n |publisher=Colorado College \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527184750/http://www.coloradocollege.edu/dept/hy/Faculty/Blasenheim.html \n |archivedate=2011-05-27 \n}}</ref>\n* [[Thomas Cronin]], political scientist and author\n* [[Edward Diller]], German literary scholar and author\n* [[Idris Goodwin]], playwright, hip hop artist, educator, and co-creator/co-host of serial radio broadcasts<ref>{{cite web|title=Critical Karaoke|url=http://www.criticalkaraoke.com|website=Critical Karaoke|accessdate=2017-07-15}}</ref>\n* [[Jesse Glenn Gray|J. Glenn Gray]], philosopher, author and translator\n* [[Steven Hayward (Canadian writer)|Steven Hayward]], Canadian author<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hayward|first1=Steven|title=Don't Be Afraid|date=2011|publisher=Knopf Canada|isbn=978-0676977363|pages=[https://archive.org/details/dontbeafraid0000hayw/page/313 313]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/dontbeafraid0000hayw/page/313}}</ref> and co-creator/co-host of serial radio broadcasts<ref>{{cite web|title=Critical Karaoke|url=http://www.criticalkaraoke.com|website=Critical Karaoke|accessdate=2017-07-15}}</ref>\n* Anne F. Hyde, historian, author, 2012 Bancroft Prize winner,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://library.columbia.edu/content/libraryweb/news/libraries/2012/20120314_bancroftprize.html |title=Winners of the 2012 Bancroft Prize Announced |accessdate=2012-12-10}}</ref> 2012 Pulitzer Prize finalist<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pulitzer.org/finalists/2012 |title=2012 Finalists |accessdate=2012-12-10}}</ref>\n* [[Dan Johnson (economist)|Dan Johnson]], [[microeconomist]] and [[entrepreneur]]\n* [[David Mason (writer)|David Mason]], poet\n* Douglas Monroy, historian<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www2.coloradocollege.edu/dept/hy/Faculty/Monroy.html\n |accessdate  = 2012-02-29\n |title       = Douglas Monroy\n |publisher   = Colorado College\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110527183624/http://www.coloradocollege.edu/dept/hy/Faculty/Monroy.html\n |archivedate = 2011-05-27\n}}</ref>\n* Carol Neel, medieval historian<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www2.coloradocollege.edu/dept/hy/Faculty/Neel.html\n |accessdate  = 2012-02-29\n |title       = Carol L. Neel\n |publisher   = Colorado College\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110527184958/http://www.coloradocollege.edu/dept/hy/Faculty/Neel.html\n |archivedate = 2011-05-27\n}}</ref>\n* [[Andrew Price-Smith]], political scientist, author on health security, environmental security, pandemic influenza\n* Tomi-Ann Roberts, social psychologist, feminist<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www2.coloradocollege.edu/dept/PY/RobertsTomiAnn.asp\n |accessdate  = 2012-02-29\n |title       = CC Psychology Department - Tomi-Ann Roberts\n |publisher   = Colorado College\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20111028060126/http://www2.coloradocollege.edu/dept/PY/RobertsTomiAnn.asp\n |archivedate = 2011-10-28\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://faculty1.coloradocollege.edu/~psych/troberts/Robertsv.html \n |accessdate=2012-02-29 \n |title=Colorado College Psychology Dept: Tomi-Ann Roberts, Vita \n |publisher=Colorado College \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140926115519/http://faculty1.coloradocollege.edu/~psych/troberts/Robertsv.html \n |archivedate=2014-09-26 \